          "content": "{\n  \"buggy_files\": [\n    \"drivers/acpi/video_detect.c\"\n  ],\n  \"buggy_functions\": [\n    \"video_detect_dmi_table\"\n  ],\n  \"confidence\": 0.95,\n  \"reasoning\": \"The Acer TravelMate 5735Z laptop has a non-functional ACPI video backlight driver by default, but works perfectly with the native intel_backlight driver when acpi_backlight=native is specified. The root cause is that the device is not present in the video_detect_dmi_table in drivers/acpi/video_detect.c. The auto-detection logic in acpi_video_get_backlight_type() at line 446 only selects native backlight for Windows 8+ systems with BACKLIGHT_RAW devices already registered. Since this is a 2011-era laptop with a pre-Windows 8 BIOS, the auto-detection fails and defaults to acpi_backlight_video, which doesn't work on this hardware. Adding a DMI quirk entry in the 'Non win8 machines which need native backlight nevertheless' section (starting at line 286) that matches the Acer TravelMate 5735Z (sys_vendor='Acer', product_name='TravelMate 5735Z' or board_name='BA51_MV') and calls video_detect_force_native() will fix this issue by forcing the use of the working native intel_backlight driver.\"\n}\n",
