          "text": "Perfect! My analysis is complete and verified. Let me create a summary of my findings:\n\n## Fault Localization Summary\n\n**Bug**: ACPI video backlight brightness control does not work on Acer TravelMate 5735Z by default, but works when `acpi_backlight=native` is specified.\n\n**Root Cause Analysis**:\n\n1. **The Device**: Acer TravelMate 5735Z (Board: BA51_MV) - An Intel GM45/GMA 4500MHD laptop from 2011\n2. **The Problem**: The ACPI video backlight driver (`acpi_backlight_video`) doesn't work on this hardware\n3. **The Solution That Works**: Using the native intel_backlight driver from the i915 DRM driver (via `acpi_backlight=native`)\n4. **Why It's Not Automatic**: The auto-detection logic in `acpi_video_get_backlight_type()` (video_detect.c:446) only selects native backlight for Windows 8+ systems. Since this laptop has a pre-Windows 8 BIOS (from 2011), it defaults to the buggy `acpi_backlight_video` driver.\n\n**The Fix**: Add a DMI quirk entry to `/workspace/drivers/acpi/video_detect.c` in the `video_detect_dmi_table` (in the \"Non win8 machines which need native backlight nevertheless\" section at line 286) that matches the Acer TravelMate 5735Z and calls `video_detect_force_native()`.\n\n**Files and Structures to Modify**:\n- **File**: `drivers/acpi/video_detect.c`\n- **Data Structure**: `video_detect_dmi_table` (line 112-377) - missing an entry for this device\n\nThe fault localization result has been written to `/workspace/fault_localization_result.json` with high confidence (0.95).",
